Register to join our upcoming Regenesis x UTERN Retreat at the link in our bio! 

Regenesis is a community environmental organization dedicated to empowering students to address today’s environmental and social concerns through advocacy and local service.

The University of Toronto’s Student Environmental Resource Network (UTERN) is a levy organization that operates as a funding body and networking hub for any person, group or club within the university community interested in sustainability and environmentalism on campus. 

As part of both organizations’ missions we believe it is critical to get environmental activists from across all three UofT campuses for networking, learning and celebration!  To this end we are hosting a retreat. All groups wishing to receive funding in the 2024-2025 school year should send representation. 

The retreat will feature:
- Learning opportunities, including workshops on various topics
- Overnight (two nights) camping at Bluewater Outdoor Education Centre (indoors, beds provided) 
- Cooking together shared meals
- Social and recreational opportunities, including a nature hike, a sauna, karaoke and board games 

The retreat will be held from August 9th to August 11th at only $25/day. 

Financial support, transportation, accommodation and food will be provided.

🌎Happy Earth Day from the Regenesis community, where every day is an opportunity to cultivate a greener, more sustainable future.

Together, let's honor our planet's beauty, cherish its resources, and commit to nurturing its health for generations to come.

Robotics for Space eXploration (RSX) is UofT’s Faculty of Applied Science and Engineering’s affiliated Mars Rover design team. As a team of passionate robotics engineers and space enthusiasts, we design, build, and compete with Mars Rovers to tackle missions such as in-situ life-detection testing, autonomous navigation, and equipment servicing. All students are welcome to join RSX regardless of your program, department, or year. Our subteams include Mechanical, Electrical, Software, Arm, Science, CANSAT, and Marketing and Events. We look forward to seeing what you explore, create, and learn with us!

Welcome back to the recap of day 3, our final day at URC! 🎉🥳✅

Day 3 had both the Equipment Servicing and Autonomous Navigation Missions back to back. During the Equipment Servicing mission, the rover arm was successfully able to place a science sample into a secured drawer then unlatch a hinged panel and type commands on a keyboard following instructions on a computer display 🧪💻. The arm’s ability to perform these complex operations with high precision and accuracy was incredibly advantageous for our score!! 🥳

For the Autonomous Navigation mission, the rover autonomously traversed to GPS dictated locations and identified ARUCO tags that signified its progress. Despite this being one of the most challenging missions of the competition, the rover successfully moved autonomously to nearby location, and our Software team is working hard to improve the rover’s autonomous traversal! 🦾

These were the final missions of the competition! We hope you all enjoyed following with us during URC!! 🚀🔭 stay tuned for our results! 👀

We finally have the recap of our second day at URC! 🥳

We faced many difficulties with this task that unfortunately affected our final score, but the judges were nonetheless very impressed with how we handled the situation under pressure, and how we did our best to correct any issues that impacted the overall task 🤩

The task for day 2 was the delivery mission, where the rover had to traverse over somewhat rough terrain to find, identify, and collect a sedimentary rock called Breccia 🔭 While we unfortunately could not collect the rock, our science lead did a fantastic job in identifying it among several others. We are so proud of our team and how we all managed throughout this competition, day 2 included! 🎉🎉

Stay tuned for the next recap and for URC results!
